    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2538083823" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2538083823" />
    <a title="xjm" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/75925423-xjm"><img alt="xjm" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2538083823?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="xjm" class="user" itemprop="url" name="xjm" href="/user/show/75925423-xjm">xjm</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6643048-the-masterharper-of-pern">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2538083823" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2260491490514854843">It&apos;s hard to give a Pern book a low rating, but this book... really isn&apos;t all that good. It reads like mediocre Pern fanfic. Actually, I think I wrote better Pern fanfic when I was nine.<br/><br/>McCaffrey&apos;s work always had its little lumps. Her prose isn&apos;t particularly stunning (<i>Dragonflight</i> especially is rough around the edges). Details and endings are often a bit saccharine. Conflicts are a bit melodramatic and villains are a bit shallow (Fax, Kylara, Meron, Pona, Toric, Avril Bitra...) The retelling o</span>
  <span id="freeText2260491490514854843" style="display:none">It's hard to give a Pern book a low rating, but this book... really isn't all that good. It reads like mediocre Pern fanfic. Actually, I think I wrote better Pern fanfic when I was nine.<br /><br />McCaffrey's work always had its little lumps. Her prose isn't particularly stunning (<i>Dragonflight</i> especially is rough around the edges). Details and endings are often a bit saccharine. Conflicts are a bit melodramatic and villains are a bit shallow (Fax, Kylara, Meron, Pona, Toric, Avril Bitra...) The retelling of the same events in different books gets old; I'm pretty sure there are two books about every major event. And of course there are little continuity flaws here and there. (I forgave Moreta's Ride being different in <i>Moreta</i> than in the original trilogy because it's quite believable in-world that the characters of the 9th Pass would get the details wrong after 1000 years, but little things like T'Kil somehow being given a rider honorific at birth and Menolly being given a retcon 10th fire lizard were minor irritants for me even as a child.)<br /><br />But the works overall usually more than make up for these things: the fantastic worldbuilding balances out run-of-the-mill prose, villains at least <i>have</i> motivations beyond Just Being Evil, and I'll gladly put up with minor continuity issues for Pern's otherwise mind-blowing, century-spanning time travel story arcs.<br /><br />This book is not like that. It's all of the flaws and none of the awesome. The plot is as boring as the writing is bad. All the characters are stock characters; all the plot points are tropes. <br /><br />The worst for me is that the continuity errors against the rest of the canon are utterly jarring. Most major characters bear no resemblance to the people they are later in the series, in ways that no character development could account for. The Charter was rediscovered in <i>All The Weyrs of Pern</i>, and <i>The Skies of Pern</i> hinges on it having been forgotten, yet somehow is known in detail to harper and holder alike here in the 8th Interval. Robinton was always startled when dragons addressed him and dragons bespeaking him is crucial to the climax of <i>All The Weyrs</i>, yet here he's been having banal conversations with every damn dragon since age 5. Most disappointingly: sexism and gender inequality are huge themes of the series, and the gradual dismantling of gender barriers in different parts of society is a major development overall and central to the character arcs for Lessa, Menolly, Mirrim, Jancis, etc... yet somehow here, 50 years earlier, we have female harpers, female holders, female craftswomen.<br /><br />Also, ugh, the names. Honorifics are formed differently than in the rest of the series. Lytol has somehow acquired an extra syllable. Every new character is Krv'thunprononunceable or Randomsyllableth.<br /><br />Yeah. Meh. I don't think I would have liked this book even back when I spent so many childhood days drawing fire lizards and writing Impression stories.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2260491490514854843" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

