<div id="review_2549028350" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2549028350" />
    <a title="Hanneke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78109870-hanneke"><img alt="Hanneke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1531052832p2/78109870.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2549028350?book_show_action=true">Oct 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hanneke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hanneke" href="/user/show/78109870-hanneke">Hanneke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/78109870-hanneke?shelf=dragon">dragon</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2549028350" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6153977758778206121">Anne McCaffrey knows how to write a story that reads away easily and this book is no exception.<br/>Still... is a must-read in the world of Pern? Not in my opinion.<br/><br/>In this book we read about a well loved character Robinton, the Masterhaper of Pern. I loved his character in the other books, and therefor was looking forward to read more about him. <br/>And although it was an easy read, it was not a fullfilling read. It was all just.... plain.<br/><br/>I read Pern for the dragons! And would have loved to read more abo</span>
  <span id="freeText6153977758778206121" style="display:none">Anne McCaffrey knows how to write a story that reads away easily and this book is no exception.<br />Still... is a must-read in the world of Pern? Not in my opinion.<br /><br />In this book we read about a well loved character Robinton, the Masterhaper of Pern. I loved his character in the other books, and therefor was looking forward to read more about him. <br />And although it was an easy read, it was not a fullfilling read. It was all just.... plain.<br /><br />I read Pern for the dragons! And would have loved to read more about the relations between Weyr, Hall and Hold. Get to read more about the dragons! There is after all a big gold one on the cover. But we do not get that, although we do get an enjoyable -plain I will say it again- book.<br /><br />Why the 2 stars and not 3? Did I mention I found it a plain story? Well that ofcourse. Also I am not a big fan of repetition. And the last 70 pages or so is almost a repetition of Dragonflight but from a different set of eyes. It is a good story (a well loved story by me), but still... repetition! If I want that story, I take that book and it does not add anything to the story of the Masterharper.<br /><br />--SPOILERS IN THE NEXT PART-<br /><br />So we read that the childhood of Robinton was not as bad as some, and not as good as some. A father that did not want to share the attention of his wife with his (newborn) son. A hall full of masters that loved and adore this young child and the potention that is in him. Not a bad deal, could have traded worst. We read about how Robinton learned the trade of Harper, who his masters were (alot of names there), in which Hold he played (again alot of names) and how he traveled there.<br /><br />We learn about his good relations with... almost everybody except the ones we hate and despite ourself (like Fax). We bond over the tragedy that overtakes Robinton when he loses his wife (again we knew something like this would happen, since there is no mention of a wife in other books).<br /><br />We learn a lot about the live of Robinton, but after reading it I can conclude that I had not missed out on any vital information all those years (and all those other books). I would have rater read about F'nol or the Weyr before Dragonflight.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6153977758778206121" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


